        "text": "\"The conception of the object of knowledge as constructed or reproduced explains why this constructivism shifts from the question WHAT or WHY first to the question HOW.[...] HOW reality is constructed must be answered in order to clarify WHAT constitutes it. But the shift to the HOW question has another meaning: it represents a turning away from perspectives that argue objectivistically. This turning away pushes the HOW question between itself and substantive theories. HOW is a categorization, a distinction or segmentation of the world operationalized by participants? How does it change and what is it used to effect? Let's take an example: 'understanding music', according to this view, is not to be answered objectivistically, by adding an objective clarification of 'understanding' plus an objective clarification of music, for instance by recourse to hermeneutics, semiotics and musicology. Rather, under this title of music understanding, one will assume a categorization of participants, whose genealogy, semantic embedding as well as pragmatic form of operation can be the subject of constructivist analyses. HOW the participants handle the category 'understanding music', what work it does for certain groupings, how it changes historically, how it is operationalized and staged, these are questions of a methodology that stengently [sic!; R.B.] relativizes the object domain to the participant level. In such a methodology, there can be no definition of an object that would be independent of the semantics that describe that object in the language of the constructing domain, and there can be no phenomenal domain that could be specified independently of the mechanisms of construction of that domain, independently of the resources and strategies that participants bring to bear to maintain and change the phenomenal domain.\" {Knorr-Cetina 1989 #21475: 92} \n\n"
      },
      "after": "d536bc86ff6b9758",
      "date": 1657792772005
